properties.location: Murray River downstream of Tocumwal to Barham
properties.webBody:
This Flood Watch is being issued for the Murray River downstream of Tocumwal to Barham.

Upstream flows from the Murray River combined with floodwaters from the Goulburn River catchment may cause minor flooding along the Murray River at Barham. Murray River at Torrumbarry and  Echuca are expected to remain below the minor flood level.

Murray River downstream of Tocumwal to Barham: 
Minor flooding may occur along the Murray River at Barham.   

The Murray River at Barham is currently at 5.06 metres and rising, below the minor flood level (5.50 metres). The Murray River at Barham may reach the minor flood level (5.50 m) over the weekend.

This warning is for communities in Victoria. Floods have different impacts on either side of the Murray River. For information and warnings relevant to NSW, visit www.hazardwatch.gov.au. Always follow advice from your State’s emergency services
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • Stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • River levels may be higher than normal
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 13/10/2023 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

This Community Information message is being issued for Dutson Downs, Golden Beach, Goon Nure, Hollands Landing, Lake Wellington, Loch Sport, Meerlieu, Ocean Grange, Paradise Beach, Seacombe, Banksia Peninsula. 

  • Firefighters are working on several hot spots, clearing debris around the fire affected area and removing any identified hazardous trees. 
  • Please obey all traffic management signage and directions and slow down to 40 km per hour when passing emergency vehicles.  This is for your own safety and for the safety of our firefighter.
  • Smoke will be visible from nearby communities and roads.
  • Recent rainfall has assisted with fire suppression, however communities need to remain aware of fires near them and monitor changes in conditions. 
There is no immediate threat to the community and no action is required.
This message was issued by Department of Environment, Land, Water & Planning.

The next update is expected by 14/10/2023 11:30 am or as the situation changes.

Minor Flood Warning for the Latrobe River

MINOR FLOODING TO CONTINUE AT ROSEDALE FOR THE NEXT FEW DAYS

Minor flooding is likely to continue along the Latrobe River at Rosedale for the next few days.

Rainfall totals of 10-25 mm are forecast across the Latrobe River catchments on Thursday, which may cause renewed river level rises. The situation is being closely monitored.

Latrobe River downstream of Traralgon:

Minor flooding is continuing along the Latrobe River downstream of Traralgon.

The Latrobe River at Rosedale (Main Stream) is currently at 4.31 metres and steady, above the minor flood level (4.00 m). The Latrobe River at Rosedale (Main Stream) is likely to remain above the minor flood level for the next few days.

Flood Safety Advice:

SES advises that all community members should:
  • Never walk, ride or drive through floodwater, Never allow children to play in floodwater, Stay away from waterways and stormwater drains during and after heavy rain.
  • Keep well clear of fallen power lines
  • Be aware that in fire affected areas, rainfall run-off into waterways may contain debris such as ash, soil, trees and rocks, and heavy rainfall increases the potential for landslides and debris across roads. 

Current Emergency Information is available at
http://emergency.vic.gov.au 
For emergency assistance contact the SES on 132 500.
Current Road and Traffic Information is available at the VicTraffic website: http://traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au/ Next Issue:
The next warning will be issued by 12:30 pm EDT on Friday 13 October 2023.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 

  • Boating in floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers. 
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. Don’t swim, drink or wash in stagnant water.
  • For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 12:30 pm EDT on Friday 13 October 2023.  or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
Community Contacts  (click for community contacts)
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This is a Final Flood Warning for Thomson River.

MINOR FLOODING HAS EASED AT SALE WHARF  

No significant rainfall has been recorded in the 24 hours to 9:00 am Wednesday. Rainfall totals of 2-10 mm are forecast across the Thomson River catchment for Thursday with isolated higher totals of 15-25 mm possible.
Renewed river level rises are possible along the Thomson River with forecast rainfall, but are likely to remain below the minor flood level.

Thomson River downstream of Wandocka:

No further flooding is expected in the Thomson River downstream of Wandocka.

The Thomson River at Sale Wharf is currently at 2.38 metres and steady, below minor flood level. 
The Thomson River at Sale Wharf is expected to remain below the minor flood level (2.40 m).
The threat of flooding is reduced. Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and beware of hazards remaining in the warning area.
What you should do:

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.

If your home or business has been flooded:
  • Check for building damage before you enter.
  • Have all electrical and gas equipment professionally tested before use.
  • Clean and dry out the building as soon as possible.

Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. For emergency assistance from the SES call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Damage to roads and buildings caused by flooding may still exist in your area. 
  • Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. Don’t swim, drink or wash in stagnant water.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

This will be the last warning for this flood. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Goulburn River from Eildon to Seymour.

MINOR FLOODING CONTINUES DOWNSTREAM OF LAKE EILDON AND SEYMOUR

Minor flooding is continuing along the Goulburn River Downstream (D/S) of Lake Eildon, Trawool and Seymour. 

Goulburn Murray Water has advised the releases from Lake Eildon are likely to drop to 15,000 ML/d for the remainder of Wednesday into Thursday when releases will be reviewed again.

No significant rainfall has been observed since 9:00 am Tuesday. Moderate rainfall is possible during Thursday but is not expected to produce renewed flooding.

Goulburn River Lake Eildon to Seymour:

Minor flooding is continuing along the Goulburn River from downstream of Lake Eildon to Seymour. Minor flooding is easing at Trawool. 

The Goulburn River downstream of Lake Eildon is currently at 3.43 metres and steady, with minor flooding. 

Based on Goulburn Murray Water's planned releases from Lake Eildon, the Goulburn River downstream of Lake Eildon is likely to remain above the minor flood level (3.00 metres) into Thursday.

The Goulburn River at Seymour is currently at 3.85 metres and falling slowly, with minor flooding. 

The Goulburn River at Seymour is likely to remain around the minor flood level (3.80 m) during Wednesday into Thursday.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Review your emergency plan and check your emergency kit is fully stocked, if you have one.
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock, pumps and machinery to higher ground. 
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Parks, hiking tracks and campgrounds are closed due to flooding. To find out more go to www.parkweb.vic.gov.au/safety/flood-affected-parks.
  • The Goulburn River Caravan Park at Seymour may start to flood low lying parts.
  • The Caravan Parks at Molesworth and the Breakaway Caravan Park at Acheron has enacted their emergency plans.
  • Localised flooding along the river frontage between Kings Park and the old Hume Highway.   
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 12/10/2023 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
  • For road closure information go to www.traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au or phone 13 11 70.
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

This Community Information message is being issued for Briagolong, Cobbannah, Culloden, Fernbank, Glenaladale, Hunter Corner, Iguana Creek, Lindenow South, Moornapa, Munro, Stockdale, Walpa, Woodglen and surrounding areas.

  • The bushfire at Duffy Rd, Briagolong is not yet under control.
  • Recent rain has dampened fire activity. However, there is still active fire within the area as logs and trees continue to burn.
  • You may see isolated pockets of flames and smoke over the burnt area.
  • Firefighters are strengthening the fire edge by blacking out
  • Several roads are still closed due to active fire and hazardous trees.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au/) or call 13 11 70 for road closures.
There is no immediate threat to the community and no action is required.

A community meeting is being held at Glenaladale:
Wednesday 11/10/23 - Glenaladale Recreation Reserve at 7:00pm 
This message was issued by Forest Fire Management Victoria.

The next update is expected by 14/10/2023 12:30 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:

properties.webBody:
This is a Final Minor Flood Warning for Yarra River from Coldstream to Warrandyte. 

  • This is an update, replacing the Advice message issued at 11:46 AM Tuesday 10 October 2023.
  • The Yarra River catchment has recorded no significant rainfall since 09:00 AM Monday 09 October 2023. 
  • No rain is forecast for the catchment for Wednesday 11 October 2023.
  • Water levels in the Yarra River and Watts Rivers are continuing to recede after last week's rain event. 
  • Dangerous hazards including floodwater, mud, debris, damaged roads and fallen trees may still be present.
Yarra River from Coldstream to Warrandyte:

  • The level of the Yarra River at Yarra Glen is currently at 3.69 metres, dropping below the Minor Flood Level (4.10 metres) yesterday evening.
The threat of flooding is reduced. Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and beware of hazards remaining in the warning area.
What you should do:

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Be aware of driving hazards, such as mud, debris, damaged roads and fallen trees. 
  • Floodwater is toxic. If properties have been impacted by flood water, please consider the following: 
Contaminated sandbags must be disposed of carefully and never reused.  It is important for your health to dispose of, or properly clean, contaminated items to stay safe from dangerous mould, chemicals, and biologic hazards in floodwater. Drinking water may be contaminated, so seek out information to confirm it.

If your home or business has been flooded:

  • Check for building damage before you enter.
  • Have all electrical and gas equipment professionally tested before use.
  • Clean and dry out the building as soon as possible.

Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. For emergency assistance from the SES call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 

  • Damage to roads and buildings caused by flooding may still exist in your area. 
  • Heavy rainfall may lead to an increased risk of landslides – be aware of fallen earth, rocks, debris or trees.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
  • Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. Don’t swim, drink or wash in stagnant water.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

This will be the last warning for this flood. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
